<ext_description linkend="Part_and_version_identification_arm.Part">
<p>
	A <b>Part</b> is a type of <express_ref linkend="product_identification:arm:Product_identification_arm.Product"/>
	that collects the definitional information of the versions of  either a 
	<module_ref linkend="part_and_version_identification:3_definition">part</module_ref> 
	or of a 
	<module_ref linkend="part_and_version_identification:3_definition">non-countable material</module_ref>.
</p>
	<note number="1">A <b>Part</b> does not represent an actual physical object that is or was existing in the real world.</note>
	<note number="2">
		A complex instance of the <b>Part</b> entity and of the 
		<express_ref linkend="Document_and_version_identification:arm:Document_and_version_identification_arm.Document">Document</express_ref> 
		entity may be created in order to represent a document that is a component of a manufactured product, for example a user manual of a car.
	</note>
	</ext_description>

  <!--
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Part_and_version_identification_arm  Entity: Part_version
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
  -->
   <ext_description linkend="Part_and_version_identification_arm.Part_version">
A <b>Part_version</b> is a type of <express_ref linkend="product_version:arm:Product_version_arm.Product_version"/>

 that identifies a version of a part.  A <b>Part_version</b> serves as the collector
 of the data characterizing a realizable object in various  application contexts. 
<note>A <b>Part_version</b> is expected to be functionally and physically interchangeable with the other versions of the same <express_ref linkend="part_and_version_identification:arm:Part_and_version_identification_arm.Part"/>.</note>
   </ext_description>

  <!--
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
